# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2016-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Democratic governor Earl Ray Tomblin was barred from running for a second full term.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2016-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] He had ascended to the governorship upon Joe Manchin's resignation in 2010, won a 2011 special election to complete the term, and won a full term in 2012.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2016-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Under the West Virginia Constitution, a partial term counts toward the limit of two consecutive terms.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2016-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Democratic nominee Jim Justice, a hotelier and coal baron, won the open seat with a plurality of the vote, defeating Republican state senator Bill Cole and former state senator Charlotte Pritt, who ran as a member of the Mountain Party.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2016-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] As of 2024, this is the last time a Democrat was elected governor of West Virginia, the last West Virginia gubernatorial race where the winner won less than 61% of votes, and the last West Virginia gubernatorial race where the winner did not win every county.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2016-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Justice switched parties in August 2017 and was re-elected as a Republican in 2020; his party switch gave Republicans the governorship for the first time since 2001 and a trifecta in the state for the first time since 1931.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2016-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] In November 2010, Democratic governor Joe Manchin resigned after being elected to the U.S.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2016-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Earl Ray Tomblin, the president of the West Virginia Senate (with the honorary title of lieutenant governor), became acting governor, won an October 2011 special election to complete the term, and won a full term in the regularly scheduled 2012 election.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2016-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Tomblin was ineligible to run for re-election in 2016, as the Constitution of West Virginia limits governors to two consecutive terms regardless of whether they are full or partial terms.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2016-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] However, governors are re-eligible after four years out of office.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2016-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] After publicly speculating he would run for his former office, Manchin was considered a heavy favorite in the 2016 race, but he announced on April 19, 2015, that he would remain in the Senate instead.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2016-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] → Indicates an internal poll conducted by the West Virginia Republican Party for Bill Cole.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2016-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Justice won two of three congressional districts, which both elected Republicans.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] The **2018 Arizona teachers' strike** was held from April 26–May 3, 2018, by 20,000 teachers to protest low pay and cuts to school funding.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Arizona Governor Doug Ducey had approved a proposal giving a 20 percent raise to teachers by 2020, with a 9 percent raise in 2019; teachers rejected this proposal as it did not provide increased funding for schools themselves or raises for support staff.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] It coincided with a similar strike in neighboring Colorado.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] The walkout occurred after similar actions in West Virginia and Oklahoma, and was the third in a wave of teachers' strikes in the United States.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] It was the first such action by teachers in Arizona.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] The strike ended on May 3, 2018, when the Government of Arizona conceded to increase funding to increase salaries for support staff and to decrease student to counselor ratios.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Teachers began holding "walk-ins" the week of April 9, during which they protested in favor of increased funding while on school campuses, and discussed the reasons for the protests with parents and interested parties.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Teachers also wore red to school to indicate solidarity.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] These protests were organized by Arizona Educators United, and were planned in part on social media.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Arizona lawmakers originally offered teachers a 1 percent raise in 2018, with an additional 1 percent raise in 2019.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Doug Ducey, the Arizona governor, further indicated that demands for a 20 percent raise were unlikely to be satisfied, and that there would be no increase in taxes to increase education spending.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Contradicting his earlier statements, Ducey announced on April 13 that there would be a 20 percent raise for teachers in the form of a 10 percent raise in 2019 and a 10 percent raise in 2020, and that $1 billion in funding cut over the past decade would be restored.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] When announced, Ducey did not discuss how the increases would be funded.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] The announcement was met with skepticism from labor organizers.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Before the walkout, teachers' salaries in 2018 were between $8000 and $9000 lower than teachers' salaries in 1990, when adjusted for inflation.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Wages for teachers in Arizona were some of the lowest in the United States, averaging $48,372 per year at the time.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] In 2017, Arizona ranked last of all fifty states for average elementary school pay, and second to last for teacher pay at the secondary level.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Since the Great Recession, funding in the state had been cut by 14 percent.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Cuts had been further exacerbated by the privatization trend in the state, which had led to job insecurity.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Teachers voted on April 19 to begin a walkout on April 26.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Of the 57,000 individuals who voted, 78 percent were in favor of a walkout.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] The decision to walk out was in part precipitated by an unstable plan to fund governor Ducey's proposal from earlier in April, which would have created a $265 million deficit after its rollout.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] During the walkout, teachers organized various events, both to discuss their motivations with the public and to guarantee students reliant on subsidized meals still received food.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] On May 1, teachers agreed to end the walkout if Arizona lawmakers passed a new budget with both raises and increased spending on schools.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] The strike officially ended after the budget was passed on May 3.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] AEU demands include a 20 percent raise for all teachers and staff during the 2018–2019 school year, the return of funding to pre-Recession levels, and a decrease in class size to a student to teacher ratio of 23:1.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Democratic legislators in the Arizona House endorsed the planned walkout.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Rebecca Rios referred to it as "brave and righteous".
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-arizona-teachers-strike] Governor Ducey, on Twitter, condemned the results of the vote, expressing fears that students would be "...the ones who lose out..." if the walkout occurred.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] The **2018 Colorado teachers' strike** was a two and a half week strike that began on April 27, 2018, with teachers in some districts across the state walking out to protest low pay, low state-wide education spending, and mismanagement of the state teachers' pension.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] The strike ended on May 12, 2018 with an agreement between the teachers' union and school officials for a 2 percent pay raise.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] The strike was part of the larger wave of teachers' strikes in the United States where protests occurred in West Virginia, Oklahoma and Arizona.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] One of the largest reasons for decreasing teacher pay and less funding for schools is the large amount of money diverted from current budgets to pay educators' unfunded pension liabilities.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] A 2016 study found that only 30% of the money that school districts pay towards the retirement benefits of an educator actually go toward that educator's pension, with 70% being used to pay off unfunded debt in that pension system.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] "The disparity is about twice as stark in Colorado.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] On that day, 10 school districts were closed in the state due to the strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] The topic of educational funding in various states within the United States has become a controversial subject.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] In early 2018, teachers in the states of Arizona, Colorado, North Carolina, Oklahoma, and West Virginia conducted strikes.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] In Colorado, the strikes occurred because of low teacher salaries and insignificant benefits.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] Colorado teachers were represented by the Colorado Education Association (CEA) and were opposed by officials of state government.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] The CEA demanded a two percent salary increase and a significant favorable adjustment to the Colorado Public Employees’ Retirement Association (PERA).
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] In response, on April 20, 2018, Colorado Senator Bob Gardner and Representative Paul Lundeen introduced Senate Bill 18-264.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] However, Senate Bill 18-264 was heavily criticized and was dismissed.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] Despite the threat of the bill, Colorado teachers began to strike on April 27, 2018 and continued to do so until May 12, 2018.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] Ultimately, the state government of Colorado agreed to give teachers a two percent salary increase.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] Two Republican state senators, Bob Gardner and Paul Lundeen responded by proposing a bill that would fine teachers $5,000 per day for striking and send to teachers to jail for six months for striking.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] The bill was met with harsh criticism and was killed in subcommittee on April 30, although Gardner indicated he would consider reintroducing the bill in 2019 should there be a strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] On April 30, Democratic governor, John Hickenlooper signed a $28.9 billion budget into law.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] In the law, $225 million was allocated to the state pension, and increased K-12 education funding by $150 million annually.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-colorado-teachers-strike] Additionally, public colleges and universities would receive a 9 percent increase in state funding aimed at limiting increases in tuition rates.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] The **2018 DeKalb County School District bus drivers' strike** was a strike held on April 19, 2018, by nearly 400 school bus drivers in DeKalb County, Georgia, United States.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] Inspired in part by the nationwide teacher strikes in Republican-dominated states such as West Virginia, Oklahoma and Arizona, bus drivers for DeKalb County School District planned a "sick-out" to protest low wages and little employee benefits.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] About 42 percent of bus drivers in the county participated, causing nearly 60-90 minute delays in students being picked up for school.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] As a right-to-work state, public sector employees are prohibited in Georgia from striking.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] The strike resulted in at least 7 bus drivers, particularly ones who helped organize the strike, being terminated of employment.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] The planned sick-out was in response to ongoing pay cuts and lowered benefits for school bus drivers.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] Per the website, Indeed, the average school bus driver salary in DeKalb County was $23,000, and the starting pay was around $18,000 to $19,000 per year, which is 23% below the national average.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] Stephen Green, the superintendent for DeKalb County School District met with over 300 bus drivers about concerns over pay and benefits.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] Green said he was committed to improving the pay and working conditions for bus drivers, but did not propose anything further.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] The sickout was originally planned for April 19–23, the strike was organized by several bus drivers that went under the labor group name, "DeKalb County School Bus Driver Solidarity Coalition".
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] On April 19, about 380 bus drivers participated of the 908 total, causing nearly 60-90 minute delays for the pickup of students.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] On April 20, that number decreased to 225.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] The following Monday, the number further decreased to 63.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] Stephen Green, the superintendent for DeKalb County School District condemned the strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] Green said "We have been clear from the beginning.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] We will keep an open dialogue with employees provided they work collaboratively and keep our children safe by reporting to work.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] Unfortunately, some employees chose another route, and that carries serious consequences." On April 20, seven DCSD bus drivers, that were involved in leading the strike, were terminated of employment.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] Green claimed the bus drivers in DeKalb County were among the highest paid in the Atlanta metropolitan area.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] This included pay raises in 2014 and 2015 in the response of longer work days, that drivers receive benefits despite being part-time, and that the county provides a Transportation Leadership Academy to offer career advancement for bus drivers.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] Threats of a second strike seemed possible as the Coalition demanded the fired employees be granted their employment back.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] On April 26, Green said he would host a meeting with the DeKalb County School Bus Driver Solidarity Coalition to discuss a plan to improve pay and working conditions for bus drivers.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] Leaders of the Coalition said that Green did not invite the leaders of the Coalition and hand-picked bus drivers to shift the dialogue in his favor.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-dekalb-county-school-district-bus-drivers-strike] On May 2, 2018, a change.org petition formed from the parents of DCSD urging Green to reinstate the terminated drivers.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] The **2018 North Carolina teachers' rally** was a rally and protest on May 16, 2018, with teachers in North Carolina walking out in protest of deflating wages and decreased employee benefits.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] The rally is part of the larger wave of teachers' strikes in the United States where protests occurred in West Virginia, Oklahoma, Colorado, and Arizona.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] Ahead of the protests the average salary for a teacher in North Carolina was $49,970, which ranked 44th in the nation according to a report by the National Education Association.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] Public school revenue per student in North Carolina ranked 43rd in the nation at $9,675.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] Additionally, the NCAE demanded that public schools in North Carolina increase the number of school nurses, counselors, social workers and other support personnel and expand Medicaid to improve community health.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] NCAE also demanded that the state legislature set up a statewide school construction board to fix older schools and reduce large class sizes.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] Roy Cooper, a Democrat, and the Governor of North Carolina, urged local and state officials to stop attacking teachers and unite together to support teachers and schools in the state.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] Cooper tweeted an editorial of *The Charlotte Observer*.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] Members from the North Carolina Republican Party sent out mass emails to constituents across the state explaining their support for public education and teachers.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] Joseph Kyzer, a spokesperson for House speaker Tim Moore stated that Republican leadership has continuously raised teachers salaries and that it was Democratic leadership in the state that stalled out spending.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] Teachers pointed out although salaries have increased, the increases have been modest and lagged far behind the national average, and that despite this, general education funding on supplies and per pupil spending have been continuously cut.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] A fellow Republican member, Mark Brody, who serves on the board of Union Day School in Waxhaw, N.C., called teachers protesting and the backers of the protest 'Union Thugs', that want to control the education process.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] Brody said he was speaking up because he did not want his local Union County schools or North Carolina schools in general to turn into Chicago.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] "Let the Union thugs get their way now and we are half way there," he said.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] Brody would defend his statement, but emphasize that the "thug" remark was about trade unions, and not the teachers themselves.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] The Raleigh-Durham chapter of the Industrial Workers of the World helped coordinate transportation for protestors who wished to rally with the teachers in Raleigh.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-north-carolina-teachers-walkout] Several North Carolina chapters of the Democratic Socialists of America stood in solidarity with the NCAE, and offered coordination for individuals wishing to join the protest.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] The **2018 Oklahoma teachers' walkout** began on April 2, 2018, with teachers across the state walking out to protest low pay, overcrowded classrooms, and tax cuts that resulted in lower state-wide education spending.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] It was the first such action in Oklahoma since 1990.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] The OEA declared an end to the walkout on April 12 after an agreement to increase salaries and state funding for education was reached.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] The call to end the walkout faced some objection from teachers and parents who did not believe that enough concessions were made by lawmakers.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Unlike the similar action in West Virginia, the walkout was not a "wildcat" strike, as it received endorsement from union leadership, albeit only after pressure from teachers.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] The protest occurred concurrently with similar protests in Arizona, Kentucky, North Carolina, and Colorado.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Since 2008, education spending per student in Oklahoma has fallen 28%.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Due to the decrease in funding, twenty percent of schools run on four-day weeks, and many have eliminated art and language classes and shut down sports programs.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Gains from last teachers' strike in Oklahoma, in 1990, which resulted in an agreement to lower class sizes, expand kindergarten programs, and increase teacher wages were later reversed due to budget cuts.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] The decline in funding and subsequent decline in the quality of public education has resulted in the expansion of charter schools in the state.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] In 2016, State Question 779 was placed on the ballot, but failed to gain enough votes.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] SQ 779 proposed a one cent increase in sales tax and was estimated to bring in $615 million for education funding (including educator pay raises) in its first year.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Failure of SQ 779 left many educators frustrated.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Support for a strike began to build in early March 2018, after another proposal (dubbed the "Step Up" plan) failed to pass the required 75% threshold for tax increases.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] The "Step Up" plan would have increased certain taxes and boosted teacher pay by $5,000.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Both Democrats and Republicans voted for and against the bill.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Some Democrats who voted "no" believed the plan did not go far enough to restore funding.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Plans for a strike beginning on April 2 were first floated in March.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Organizers utilized Facebook groups in planning the strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] On April 2, schools throughout Oklahoma were scheduled to take standardized tests; preventing these tests from taking place could potentially jeopardize millions in federal funds allocated to Oklahoma.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] After the Oklahoma legislature passed a tax increase to fund teach pay raises with the required 75% in each body on Friday, March 30, a strike beginning on the 2nd was announced.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Thus, even before the walkout, teachers won greater school funding and salary increases, funded in part by increases in the cigarette tax, motor fuel tax, and the gross production tax on petroleum.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] The strike lasted from April 2 to April 12.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Strike leaders had called for the introduction of a capital gains tax to avoid a regressive tax, but the terms were nevertheless accepted.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] The legislature passed no further tax increases after the walkout began.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Public school teacher salaries in Oklahoma prior to the strike were the third lowest in the United States (after South Dakota and Mississippi), resulting in some teachers and staffers working second or third jobs.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] An initial offer of a $6,000 wage increase, ratified by the governor, was rejected, as the initial demands were for a $10,000 raise for teachers and a $1250 raise for support staff.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Governor Mary Fallin likened teacher demands to "...teenager(s) wanting a better car".
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] The quote was appropriated by teachers and used in chants during protests at the Oklahoma State Capitol.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] State representative Kevin McDugle, a Republican, indicated he would not pass any bill or measure to increase education spending due to the protests undertaken by the teachers.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] A survey in 2019 found that the pay raise obtained by the strike had lifted the State's teacher pay ranking to 34th in the nation, higher than the surrounding states of New Mexico, Kansas, Missouri and Arkansas, but still lower than Colorado or Texas.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Ten Republican representatives who were opposed to raising taxes to increase teacher salaries were up for re-election in 2018.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] Two, Scott McEachin and Chuck Strohm, were eliminated by other Republican nominees during the initial primary, while a further seven did not gain enough votes to win their primaries uncontested.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-oklahoma-teachers-strike] These seven faced runoff elections in August 2018, and six lost.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] The strike, called in response to anger among teachers and other school employees over low pay and high health care costs, involved roughly 20,000 teachers and public school employees and shut down schools in all 55 West Virginia counties, affecting some 250,000 students.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] The strike inspired teachers in other states, including Oklahoma, Colorado, and Arizona, to take similar action.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] Teachers in other states, including North Carolina and Kentucky have also coordinated protests and walkouts on a smaller scale.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] The strike was called in response to the low pay of West Virginia teachers, whose compensation ranks 48th in the United States.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] The strike also responded to a pay raise passed by the legislature and signed by Governor Jim Justice that provided only a 2% raise for 2019, and 1% raise for 2020 and a 1% raise for 2021 and a freeze on premiums for 16 months to benefits.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] The teachers' unions did not release vote totals for the strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] Every public school district in the state closed to avoid confrontations.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] It was the first such strike since 1990.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] According to some analysts, West Virginia teachers had a stronger negotiating position in the strike because many teaching positions remain unfilled.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] Teachers say that because of low pay in West Virginia, the state has difficulty attracting and retaining teachers.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] One of the major issues involved funding for the Public Employees Insurance Agency, the state health insurance plan.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] The West Virginia Legislature had voted to boost state contributions to the plan by using a percentage of the annual state surplus, but the teachers' unions were demanding a more reliable financing plan.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] Health care costs have increased quickly enough that proposed teacher pay increases cannot match teacher payments for health care.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] The work stoppage took place in defiance of both state law forbidding public employee strikes and union leadership.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] On February 21, the day before the walkout, state Attorney General Patrick Morrisey warned that a strike "of any length on any ground is illegal” and said his office would support local districts attempting to enforce the state ban on public employee strikes.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] Nonetheless, on the same day, Governor Justice signed into law a bill offering teachers a 2% pay increase.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] "We need to keep our kids and teachers in the classroom," Gov.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] "We certainly recognize our teachers are underpaid and this is a step in the right direction to addressing their pay issue." Teachers said that the 2% pay raise, and subsequent raises of 1% slated for 2020 and 2021, would not keep up with inflation.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] Teachers rejected the pay raise, walking out across the state on February 22.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] The same day, a crowd estimated at 5,000 demonstrated at the West Virginia State Capitol.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] The strike continued on February 23, as all schools in the state were closed once again.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] Teachers and other workers rallied in front of the West Virginia State Capitol as well as picketed in front of individual schools.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] West Virginia teachers have a stronger negotiating position in the strike because many teaching positions remain unfilled.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] A deal reached by union leaders and Governor Jim Justice was announced on February 27, and union leaders called on teachers and other education-related personnel to return to classrooms on Thursday March 1, after a "cooling off" period.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] However, during the late evening on February 28, every county announced school closures due to continuing work stoppages, and by this point the stoppage had become a wildcat strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] On March 3, the West Virginia Senate rejected a bill passed by the West Virginia House of Delegates approving the agreed upon 5% pay rise, instead proposing a 4% pay rise, extending the strike into an eighth work day.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] A similar strike was proposed by teachers in Oklahoma, where teacher compensation is worse than in West Virginia, at 49th in the United States.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] On Sunday March 4, 1,400 West Virginia Frontier Communications workers went on strike in response to company restructuring, also citing rising health care costs, and the example of the Teacher's Strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] West Virginia school personnel returned to classrooms on Wednesday March 7 after the State Senate agreed to the House's position following conference committee negotiations.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] The strike, while achieving a 5% pay raise, did not provide guarantees to control rising health care costs.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] Justice and other Republican lawmakers opposed the strike and asserted that the teachers' absence from the classroom were hurting school children.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] He also said there was not enough money to fund teachers' demands. “I’m telling you when we should do more is when we know we can do more," Justice said on February 23.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] "Today we think we can do more, but we don’t know.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] Our teachers need to be in the classroom.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] The Legislature has spoken and I’ve signed it into law.” Justice, a billionaire coal magnate, won election in 2016 as a Democrat with the endorsements of the AFT-WV and the WVEA, along with other unions in the state.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] He subsequently switched to the Republican Party.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] Union officials sought backing from prominent state Democratic Party leaders, inviting them to speak at teachers' demonstrations during the strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] The strike was noteworthy because it emerged from rank-and-file teachers, who began to demand statewide strike action.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] Pressure to strike was "coming from everywhere," Christine Campbell, AFT-WV president, said in early February.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] These demands coalesced into a series of rallies and demonstrations held throughout the state.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] Ultimately the strike became a wildcat when teachers refused back-to-work orders from the unions.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] The Industrial Workers of the World (IWW) issued a press release, demanding that the strike continue unless a series of demands were met, including a tax on natural gas production to fund state education.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike] A number of IWW members (Wobblies) were key contributors to the effort, including as building representatives.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The **2018 York University strike** was a strike by CUPE Local 3903, the union representing contract professors, teaching assistants, and graduate assistants at York University.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] At 143 days long it is the longest strike in the post-secondary sector in Canadian history, surpassing the previous record of the 1976 Laval University 108-day strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] It ended on July 25, when the Ontario Legislature passed the *Urgent Priorities Act* back-to-work legislation.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] York declared that the university would "remain open" and that certain classes would continue running.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] On the Friday of March 2, the newly founded Students Against Strike organized a small walk-out demonstration and demanded that undergraduate students deserved their own platform in the conflict between York University Administration and CUPE 3903.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The strike began on March 5, 2018, at 12:01 am EST.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Despite the strike, the university remained open (with all major entrances blockaded via hard picket lines), and the few winter term courses that were able to continue, continued to run.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Winter term ended on April 23 as originally scheduled.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Students that refused to participate in academic activities during the labour disruption were promised reasonable accommodations.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] On March 12, 2018, the Minister of Advanced Education and Skills Development, Mitzie Hunter, contacted CUPE 3903 and the York University administration to encourage the two sides to bargain.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] CUPE 3903 re-affirmed its willingness to bargain.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] After little movement from either side, on March 18, 2018, York University announced that it would return to the bargaining table.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] CUPE 3903 was optimistic that the disruption might be resolved but expressed disappointment when York, despite movement from CUPE 3903, issues an ultimatum to capitulate on all important issues, or York walks away from the table.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] On March 20, York University presented a revised offer and exercised their statutory power to force a one-time mandatory ratification vote.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] York made its request on March 27, but the law stipulates a two-week delay between request and vote.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The vote was held between April 6 and April 9.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The university's offer was rejected by 85% of those who voted, with 2,320 "no" votes cast.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] With the ratification vote defeated, the strike continued.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] According to CUPE, the proposal under consideration was not meaningfully different from the offer that they rejected at the beginning of the strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] CUPE 3903 subsequently filed an unfair labor practices complaint with the Ontario Labour Relations Board.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The complaint alleged that York publicly mischaracterized CUPE 3903 demands, incorrectly characterized the demands as illegal, and during a previous labour disruption appropriated the domain name CUPE3903.com to direct internet searches for information on CUPE to the university's own labour page.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] York responded that the objections were without merit.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] CUPE 3903 would learn that "CUPE3903.com" was billed to York University by Michael Schiff, an employee in the office of the Faculty of Graduate Studies.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] During the strike, a coalition of socialist student groups, Students for CUPE 3903, staged an occupation of the University Senate chambers in support of the strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Participants protested potential expense account issues from Lenton's term as Vice President Academic and President, in addition to various other tuition-oriented concerns.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Simultaneously, a website publishing documents relating to Lenton's expenses, Yorked.me, was registered under a false identity.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Yorked.me was taken down following a copyright complaint from the university, but resurfaced as Yorked.tk, using a free domain name.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Early demands from Students for CUPE 3903 included the cancellation of classes that were not taught by CUPE 3903 members.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The ultimate authority to make academic policy (of which disruption policy is a part), according to the York Act, rests with York's Senate.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Many classes taught by members of York's full-time faculty continued, though many of these classes experienced varying levels of disruption ranging from marking not being completed to classes being suspended entirely.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Classes taught by contract faculty were already suspended owing to their instructors being on strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Lenton and the Board of Governor's move to take control of academic policy from the Senate received the unanimous censure of the Canadian Association of University Teachers (CAUT), an organization representing most all academic staff in Canada.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] According to CAUT, not only was this in contravention with past practice, but it was also in contravention of the *York Act*, the act of the Legislature of Ontario that created York University.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Minor incidents of violence occurred as students were stopped at picket lines.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] A video was released by picketers showing a student dismantling barricades at the Northwest Gate picket line in an attempt to attend his Midterm exam.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The student was placed in a chokehold by a picketer, upon breaking free the student kicked the picketer in retaliation.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] A picketer was injured after a vehicle forced its way past a picket line.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Protesters demonstrated outside a university senate meeting and attempted to prevent senators from entering.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] During the melee, a teaching assistant senator was put in a headlock by security and prevented from entering.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] CUPE 3903 protestors picketed at the house of York University President Rhonda Lenton.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] On April 13, 2018, Kevin Flynn, Minister of Labour, appointed labour relations lawyer William Kaplan as the sole member of an Industrial Inquiry Commission.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The purpose of such an inquiry is to create a report on the status of a labour dispute, for the minister, and in the process bring the two sides in a dispute together.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] CUPE revised their offer, with more concessions in favour of the employer.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] York University in its submission to the inquiry argues that CUPE 3903 is too radical to bargain with, and cites the writings of some of its members (all academics) as proof of a "mentality" that York cannot negotiate with.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] From the start of the labour disruption, York University adopted a hard line on its offer, and urged CUPE to accept it, or agree to arbitration.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] At the conclusion of the inquiry, Kaplan noted in his report that "the parties have reached an impasse and there is no reason to believe that they will be able to resolve their dispute through free collective bargaining.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The precise date that the report was made available to the province, the University and CUPE 3903 was not certain.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] However, details of the report (which was meant primarily for the Minister) were leaked to the press and made public on Friday May 4, 2018.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] CUPE 3903 maintained its position that bargaining and not arbitration was the means to resolve the impasse.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Leading up to the Industrial Commission, York University claimed that its bargaining priorities had the support of York's academics, without reference or substantiation.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The York University Faculty Association objected, and noted that the only basis for this claim was an open letter in support of these prioritise by a group of 152 full-time academics, which YUFA notes comprises 10% of its members.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] While not claiming that YUFA members are unanimous about various issues at stake in the labour dispute, YUFA rejected the idea that its membership was in favour of the University's position in the labour dispute.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] One signatory of the letter, Rose Steele, a professor in the School of Nursing, claimed that fear of "retributions" from CUPE 3903 and YUFA were suppressing public dissent among CUPE and YUFA members.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] On April 19, York University published a statement warning that S2 term (June–August) would be cancelled if the strike continued past April 30.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] On May 2, York University published a statement announcing they would commence the summer term (SU and S1 terms) on May 22.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] On May 7, York University issued an ultimatum to CUPE3903.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The university demanded that CUPE accept a revised offer by May 10 at 11:59 EDT, or the university will not implement a back-to-work backpay protocols and would not offer employment to members of striking CUPE units during the summer term.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] CUPE rejected the university's demands and on May 10, issued a limited-time offer of a "framework for settlement" expiring May 14.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Criticism among students has been directed at both CUPE 3903 and York University President Rhonda Lenton's poor handling of the dispute.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] In light of Kaplan's recommendation, on May 7, the Ontario government introduced Bill 70, the *York University Labour Disputes Resolution Act, 2018*.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The bill was introduced the day before the Legislature was set to be dissolved in preparation for the 2018 Ontario general election.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Opposition from the Ontario NDP slowed the passage of the bill through first reading; it was eventually carried with division.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The bill died before a second or third reading could be conducted after the government dissolved the Legislature earlier than expected.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] With the dissolution of the Legislature, the outcome of any legislation would be made after the 2018 Ontario general election.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] On June 14 and June 15, Unit 2 members of CUPE 3903 held a ratification vote on an offer for Unit 2 sent by York University on June 6.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] CUPE 3903 condemned the offer as "backroom dealings of certain members of the [Unit 2] Bargaining Team." The vote came after the results of a previous vote on the same offer were rejected over alleged irregularities.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] 231 Yes votes were cast, while 122 No votes were cast.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Following the vote, York University announced that Unit 2 members would return to work on the following Monday, June 18.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] CUPE 3903 stated that other bargaining units would remain on strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] On July 16, 2018, the newly elected 42nd Parliament of Ontario introduced Bill 2 into the legislature, formally called the *Urgent Priorities Act*.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The omnibus bill included a clause to end the labour dispute at York University.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Premier Ford argued that the back-to-work legislation was for the sake of the students, claiming that they were "the only people getting hurt" in the conflict between CUPE 3903 and York Administration.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The chairman of CUPE 3903, Devin Lefebvre, spoke out against the legislation claiming that it was a violation of workers rights.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] On July 25, 2018, Bill 2 received Royal Assent, effectively ending the York Strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The legislation gives the government the power to fine members of the York union $2,000 each day and fines the Union $25,000 for each day it continues to strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Back-to-work-legislation had influenced how some students voted in the 2018 Ontario general election and many were relieved that the strike was finally over.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] By May 2, 2018, several faculties and student groups at York University passed votes of non-confidence in Rhonda Lenton, President of York, and the Board of Governors for creating a crisis of governance and for their handling of the strike.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] The faculties include Glendon College, the Faculty of Education, the Faculty of Environmental Studies, and the Faculty of Liberal Arts & Professional Studies (LAPS), not to mention York University Graduate Students' Association (YUGSA), and a number of departments and student associations.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] As noted by YUFA, almost half of York's full-time faculty teaches in the Faculty of Liberal Arts and Professional Studies, implying that altogether, representative bodies of about (if not more than) half of York's faculty have lost confidence in York's administration.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] Concerned academics and some student groups (including York's own full-time Faculty Association) continued to support CUPE 3903 with a call to York to return to the bargaining table.
[src:2018-west-virginia-teachers-strike/2018-york-university-strike] CUPE 3903 added that York Administration had; attempted to replace bargaining with a public relations campaign, misrepresented union processes, had red lines that it refuses to discuss, and that it had decided to not put students first in its labour dispute.
